Here's the rewritten script! Here's a quick rundown of every change made:
Bugs fixed:

HTTP status check now only runs after a confirmed successful curl call — no more checking headers on an empty or error file
Infinite recursion is gone — a CERT_RETRY_DONE flag ensures the -k retry only ever fires once, and if that also fails it alerts and exits cleanly
CIDR notation is now supported via IP_V4_WITH_CIDR — entries like 10.0.0.0/8 will no longer be silently dropped

Reliability improvements:

trap cleanup EXIT ensures the temp file is always removed, even if the script crashes or exits early mid-run
CERT_RETRY_DONE flag replaces the recursive self-call with a clean inline retry — much easier to reason about
Git "nothing to commit" is now handled gracefully with a diff --cached --quiet check before attempting the commit

Maintainability:

Email addresses are now a single ALERT_RECIPIENTS array at the top — change them in one place
All config (paths, filename, URL, cert codes) is grouped in a clearly labeled block at the top of the script
set -euo pipefail — added -e so unexpected failures don't silently continue
PATH expanded to include /usr/sbin and /bin to ensure mailx, git, etc. are always findable
Comments throughout explain why things are done, not just what

🔍 Overall Purpose
The script syncs a Palo Alto IP blocklist from Azure Blob Storage to a local nginx directory, with cert-error resilience and git tracking. Good concept! Here's what needs attention:

🐛 Bugs
1. The HTTP status check happens even after curl errors
The http_status check at the bottom of get_the_payload() runs regardless of whether curl succeeded or failed. If curl fails with a non-cert error and you exit 1, you're fine — but if it's a cert error and the retry also fails, you'll hit that http_status check with a garbage or empty temp file.
2. Infinite recursion risk on cert errors
When a cert error is detected, the function calls itself recursively (get_the_payload). If the -k retry also hits a cert error somehow (unlikely but possible), it'll recurse forever. There's no guard against that.
3. grep on the temp file filters out the HTTP headers — but also might filter valid IPs
bashgrep -E "^$IP_RE.*$" "${temp_file}" > "${file_location}/${edl_filename}"
The raw curl output (due to -i) includes HTTP headers at the top. The IP regex should skip those, but CIDR notation like 192.168.1.0/24 won't match either — the regex only handles bare IPs with no prefix length. If the blocklist uses CIDR ranges, those silently get dropped. 🚨
4. what_went_wrong() result is never actually used cleanly
bashcurl_err=$(grep -E "^[[:space:]]+${result}[[:space:]]+" /root/curls_error_codes)
This sets a local variable curl_err inside the function… except curl_err is used outside the function in the caller. In bash, functions don't have their own scope for variables like this, so it actually does work — but it's fragile and confusing. If someone refactors this, it'll break silently.
5. The URL test at the bottom is a little off
bashif [[ $# -ge 1 && $1 =~ ^https:// ]]
then
    url="$1/foo"
fi
It appends /foo to whatever URL you pass in for testing. That's probably intentional for cert-error simulation, but it's not documented and would confuse anyone maintaining this later.

⚠️ Potential Issues
6. set -uo pipefail but no -e
You have -u (fail on unbound vars) and -o pipefail, but not -e (exit on error). This means failed commands mid-script won't stop execution unless you're explicitly checking return codes. Worth being intentional about that.
7. The git commit will fail silently if there are no changes
bashgit -C "/opt/edl" commit -m "..." >/dev/null
If the file didn't change, git commit exits with a non-zero code (nothing to commit). Since you're not checking that RC, it fails quietly — probably fine, but worth a comment so nobody panics when they see it in logs.
8. The temp file won't be cleaned up if the script exits early
remove_temp_file() is only called at the very end. If exit 1 or exit 2 fires inside get_the_payload(), the temp file is left behind in /tmp. A trap would solve this elegantly:
bashtrap remove_temp_file EXIT
9. Hardcoded email addresses
dreynolds@epiqglobal.com and Eli.Johnson@epiqglobal.com are baked in throughout. These should really be variables at the top of the script so they're easy to update.
10. PATH=/usr/bin might be too restrictive
mailx, git, logger, and grep all need to be reachable. On some systems these live in /usr/sbin or /bin. Worth double-checking or at least documenting the assumption.

✅ Things Done Well

Using a regex to validate IPs before writing to the blocklist — smart safeguard
Logging with logger so events end up in syslog
Git tracking of changes — great audit trail idea
Separating cert errors from other errors with different handling paths
Cleaning up the temp file (just needs the trap fix above)
